justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind responded to the government’s consultation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">“Judicial Review: Proposals for further reform</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind considers j</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">udicial review </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a key tool for ensuring that the rights of people with experience of mental health problems are protected, promoted and upheld. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The ability to hold the executive to account is a fundamental tenet of a democratic society</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind’s view is that the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">governme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">nt’s proposals will severely dilute the constitutional rights of citizens and undermine the role of the judiciary in holding public bodies accountable.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s deeply concerned about the impact of the proposals on people who expe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">rience mental health proble</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ms and we have outlined our concerns below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Standing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The proposed introduction of a narrower test for “standing” to apply for judicial review, so as to limit the range of people and groups who are entitled to invoke the procedure</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The courts </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the value of claims being brought by those without a direct interest in the proceedings:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">“Public law is not at base about rights, even though abuses of power may and often do invade private rights; it is about wrongs - that is to say misus</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">es of public power; and the courts have always been alive to the fact that a person or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> with no particular stake in the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">issue or the outcome may, without in any sense being a mere meddler, wish and be well placed to call the attention of the co</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">urt to an apparent misuse of public power. If an arguable case of such misuse can be made out on an application for leave, the court's only concern is to ensure that it is not being done for an ill motive.”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Additionally, the government itself </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">acknowledge</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">in the consultation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">that cases brought by NGOs, charities and pressure groups tend to be valid claims:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">“From Administrative Court records for cases lodged between 2007 and 2011 around 50 judicial reviews per year have been identified that app</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ear to have been lodged by NGOs, charities, pressure groups and faith </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, i.e. by claimants who may not have had a direct interest in the matter at hand. The identified cases tended to be relatively successful compared to other JR cases.”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Organisations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that bring cases as representatives of a group of individuals are best placed to provide the court with an expert view. This means that the court can focus on the underlying issue rather than on the specific facts of an individual case. The r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">isk posed by the proposal to change the rules on standing is that the courts will face a series of claims from various individuals when one would do. This would be neither cost effective nor efficient. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The proposals to limit those with standing will impact</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> on a minority of cases which are generally highly meritorious by virtue of their wider public interest.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In Mind’s view, a test for standing that is any narrower than having to demonstrate “sufficient interest” risks interfering with the right to a remedy under Article 6 ECHR.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Third Party Interventions</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: The proposed modification of the rules to discour</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">age the involvement of interveners and third parties</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Third parties make applications to intervene in a minority of cases in order to assist the court in understanding the wider implications of a case on often large numbers of people. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">intervened in a number of cases</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the majority </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of which have involved </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">breaches of individuals’ fundamental rights and freedoms</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> under human rights and equality legislation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. Some examples are given below:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Savage v </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">South Essex Partnership NHS Foundation Trust</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Rabone</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> and another v </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pennine</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Care NHS Foundation Trust</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">established </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a positive duty on hospitals to ensure that they take reasonable steps to prevent mental health patients from taking their own lives. It was a challenge relating to the application o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">f Article 2 ECH</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">MM and DM v Secretary of State for Work and Pensions</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> involves a challenge to the Employment Support Allowance (“ESA”) determination process based on the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">fact that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">it places people with mental health problems at </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">substantial </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">disadvantage.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Das v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> concern</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ed the threshold for determining whether p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">eople with mental health problems should be detained in immigration removal </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">This case was brought against the backdrop of four previ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ous cases in which the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ourt found breaches of Article 3.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">P v Cheshire West and Chester Council</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> &amp; P and Q v Surrey County Council</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> concerned the proper approach to the question of when a person is deprived of their liberty within the meaning of Article</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> 5 ECHR. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The above case examples concern matters of fundamental importance to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind’s beneficiaries and it </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is imperative, in Mind’s view, that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the rules on interveners remain as they are in order for the court to decide whether it would benefit from the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ex</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ert evidence </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">third parties </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are in a unique position to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">provide. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: The proposed rebalancing of financial incentives so that providers are only paid for work carried out on judicial review cases where permission is granted, or exceptionally</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in the Legal Aid Agency’s discretion</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Aside from the fact that the government a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ppears</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> to be suggesting that public lawyers pursue cases for reasons other than that their client has a valid claim and that the Legal Aid Agency </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">(LAA) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">grants funding for unmeritorious cases, Mind has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a number of concerns relating to this proposal.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">here is a risk that the courts will become clogged with applications for costs determinations. This can be a lengthy process and will require provider</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">subsidise</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the costs of litigation which is not viable for many firms, particularly those which undertake predominantly legal aid work. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Another</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> undesirable result of th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> proposal is that specialist public law firms, with many years experience of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">judicial review, may cease taking on judicial review cases because it is not financially viable for them to do so. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The risk is that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">non-specialist lawyers </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">attempt to turn their hand to judicial review which will increase the likelihood of unmeritoriou</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s/vexatious and poorly prepared claims being brought. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">V</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ulnerable clients, for example those wit</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">h mental health problems, sometimes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">change their mind about pursuing a claim part way through the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">process – i.e. between issuing the proceedings and permission being granted. They may choose to discontinue a claim because they find the process too stressful, or because they have a lack of tr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ust in the process as a result </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of a previous bad experience. Therefore, pr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">oviders may be less willing to act for vulnerable clients due to the risk of not getting paid.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">he introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">discretion</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> for the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">LAA</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> to pay providers in cases where proceed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ings are issued, but the case concludes prior to a permission decision, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is likely to lead to a significant number of claims being brought against the LAA. Where its application of the criteria leads to non-payment, providers will have no choice but to moun</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">t such challenges. Ironically, this would increase the number of judicial review applications made.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4.6</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">People with mental health problems are more likely to access health and community care services. Where the provision of such services is refused or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">reduced, the appropriate remedy is judicial review where all other avenues have been exhausted. If these proposals go ahead, such individuals will effectively have no remedy beyond pursuing a complaint, as they will struggle to find a lawyer able and/or wi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lling to take their case on. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Mind considers that the proposals to further curb access to legal aid risks </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">breaching </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">individuals</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> rights under Article 6 ECHR. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Public Sector Equality Duty</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: The proposal to make non-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">justiciable</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the statutory duty </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">imposed on public bodies by the Equality Act, to have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, by providing an alternative, non-judicial mechanism for resolving disputes about whether public bodies have complied with the duty</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahom