p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">             </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The combined effect of these proposals with the government’s proposals to reform legal aid, in particular th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e introduction of a residence test  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Under the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, a person detained in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">psychiatric hospital would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">be entitled </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to advice as </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">those subject to detention under the Mental Health Act are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">xc</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">luded from </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the 12 month rule. However, once discharged into the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">community, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">such an individual </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">not be entitled to legal aid to enforce their rights to social care support and housing </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">if the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> could not satisfy the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">12 month</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> residence test</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">A lack of adequate after</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">care services and/or accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">laces people </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">at serious risk of relapse and r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">admission </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to hospital</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">From enquiries to our Legal Advice Line, and from our work with advocates and service providers in local Minds, we know that some psychiatric patients, whether they have been detained or were admitted as voluntary inpatients, are discharged from hospital w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ithout any, or any adequate, aftercare services including social care support and housing. These people require legal assistance to enforce their rights. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Similarly, the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">12 month residence test will </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">not apply to those in immigration detention</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. Howeve</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">r, Home Office guidance stipulates that people with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">serious mental </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">illness which </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">cannot be satisfactorily managed in detention </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are normally considered suitable for detention in only very exceptional circumstance</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">12 month residence test </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">create</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> an </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">anomaly as those who are detained will be entitled to legal aid, but those who are living in the community, often with serious mental health problems</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and therefore significant support needs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, will not.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In a climate of increasing cuts to public services, of which people with mental health problems are often beneficiaries, the government is attempting to severely restrict the ability of individuals to challenge the decisions, acts and omissions of public b</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">odies. Combined with the further reforms to legal aid, in Mind’s opinion, the government’s plans </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">would be catastrophic</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> for people with mental health problems.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 November 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Sedley</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> J in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">R v Somerset County Council, ex p </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Dixon</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> [1998] </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Env</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> LR 111</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Paragraph 78</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">[2007] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> 1375</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> [2012] UKSC 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> 2013 UKUT 260 AAC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">[2013] EWHC 682 (Admin)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (S) v SSHD </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">[2011] EWHC 2120 (Admin), </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (BA) v SSHD </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">[2011] EWHC 979 (Admin), </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">HA (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Nigeria</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">), </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (D) v SSHD </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">[2012] EWHC 2501 (Admin</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> UKSC/2012/ 0068</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> UKSC/2012/0088P</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Chapter 55.10 Enforcement Instructions and Guidance, Home Office, August 2010</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>